Although Schumpeter emphasized the role of the financial system as the handmaiden of creative destruction, he probably overestimated its role in funding new enterprises, which was uncommon even in his day (
 
  34
 ). Most new ventures are financed by the entrepreneurs themselves or by money from family and friends (
 
  35
 ). Early-stage finance often has “affective and charitable dimensions” [(
 
  36
 ), p. 1688]. As Janeway argues, new technologies need support of a non-economic nature (
 
  20
 ). The importance of cooperation to reduce uncertainty makes it important to pay attention to the concrete relations between entrepreneurs and financiers when studying the emergence of new industries.
